        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nShe still remembers the vibration of it. At nine years old, on a field trip to the de Young, she stood before a massive, textured sculpture by Ruth Asawa. While other kids fidgeted, Isabella felt a silent hum. It was a language without words, a story told in wire and shadow. Her parents spoke of numbers and vitals, of stability. But in the museum\u2019s quiet hall, she felt a different kind of truth. It wasn\u2019t a choice to love art; it was a recognition of her native tongue.\n\n2.\nThe smell of her mother\u2019s adobo filled their Daly City kitchen, a scent of comfort that couldn't soften the conversation. It was her senior year at Berkeley, age 22. Her father, his engineer\u2019s hands folded on the table, asked about her plans. The silence after she said \"gallery work\" was heavy with disappointment. It wasn't anger, but a deep, loving fear for her. In that moment, her quiet rebellion hardened into resolve. She had to prove that a life built on passion could also be a life of substance.\n\n3.\nShe was 36, standing in a sterile downtown boardroom, presenting a mood board for a commercially safe but creatively vapid artist. The portfolio of a brilliant Mission muralist, a woman whose work pulsed with life, sat unseen in her bag. A wave of physical nausea, a kind of artistic indigestion, washed over her. It was the stark realization that she was no longer a champion for art, but a sales associate for wall decor. That hollow feeling was the catalyst that made the terror of starting her own gallery feel necessary.\n\n4.\nIt was 2 a.m. the night before Verve\u2019s first opening. She was 38, alone in the gallery, the smell of fresh paint and floor polish hanging in the air. Fear was a cold knot in her stomach; their pooled savings were in these walls, this lighting. She ran her hand over the cool, smooth surface of the front desk her friend had built, the keys to the front door heavy in her pocket. This wasn't just a business. It was an anchor, the first place that felt entirely, terrifyingly, her own.\n\n5.\nLast fall, during a packed opening, Isabella stepped back from the crowd. She watched as an artist she\u2019d championed, a young trans man from the Tenderloin, talked a wealthy couple through the fierce story in his painting. His voice was confident, their faces rapt with understanding. A warmth spread through her chest that had nothing to do with the wine. She wasn\u2019t merely the curator; she was the conduit. In that moment, Verve felt less like a gallery and more like a living, breathing promise to the city."
